  "prompt": "How do I take input from STDIN in Python?",
  "response": "In Python, there are several ways to take input from STDIN (standard input). Here are the most common methods:\n\n1. `input()` function (Python 3.x):\n```python\n# Basic input\nname = input(\"Enter your name: \")\nprint(\"Hello,\", name)\n\n# Input as integer\nage = int(input(\"Enter your age: \"))\nprint(\"You are\", age, \"years old\")\n```\n\n2. `sys.stdin.readline()`:\n```python\nimport sys\n\n# Read a single line\nline = sys.stdin.readline().strip()\n\n# Read multiple lines\nlines = sys.stdin.readlines()  # Reads all lines\n```\n\n3. Reading multiple inputs on a single line:\n```python\n# Space-separated integers\nnums = list(map(int, input().split()))\n\n# Example\na, b, c = map(int, input().split())\n```\n\n4. Reading from STDIN in competitive programming:\n```python\nimport sys\n\n# Read a single integer\nn = int(sys.stdin.readline())\n\n# Read a list of integers\narr = list(map(int, sys.stdin.readline().split()))\n```\n\n5. Handling multiple test cases:\n```python\n# Number of test cases followed by inputs\nt = int(input())\nfor _ in range(t):\n    # Read input for each test case\n    x = input()\n    print(x)\n```\n\nKey differences and tips:\n- `input()` is easier to use but slightly slower\n- `sys.stdin.readline()` is faster and more commonly used in competitive programming\n- `strip()` removes leading/trailing whitespace\n- `split()` breaks input into a list\n- `map()` can convert inputs to desired type\n\nChoose the method that best fits your specific use case.",
